You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` using `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`, and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" — cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete(); // always call this
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` before any `await`, then `deferral.Complete()` after. Without it, the navigation completes before your async dialog returns.

### 2. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 3. ViewModel command

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard dialog will fire
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 4. Expose `HasUnsavedChanges`

Add a public property on the page (or resolve it from the ViewModel):

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    public bool HasUnsavedChanges =>
        (BindingContext as EditProductViewModel)?.HasUnsavedChanges ?? false;
}
```

**How it works:** The `BackButtonBehavior` replaces the back arrow with a "Cancel" label. When tapped, it calls `GoToAsync("..")`, which triggers `OnNavigating`. The guard checks `HasUnsavedChanges`, shows the dialog, and cancels navigation if the user chooses "Stay."
